<article>
    <h1>Key dates and events</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201025/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-25"><time>2020-10-25</time></a>
        - <span>IN&#xAD;SIGHT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>DE­CEM­BER 2016</p>
    <p>King Maha Va­ji­ra­longkorn suc­ceeds his fa­ther, King Bhu­mi­bol Adulyadej, af­ter the lat­ter dies in Oc­to­ber.</p>
    <p>APRIL 2017</p>
    <p>The King signs a new Con­sti­tu­tion that takes in changes he had re­quested, paving the way for Thai­land’s next gen­eral elec­tion.</p>
    <p>MAY</p>
    <p>The King is granted con­trol over five state agencies that over­see royal af­fairs and se­cu­rity, in one of many ways he is granted more pow­ers.</p>
    <p>JUNE 2018</p>
    <p>He for­mally gains full own­er­ship of the Crown Prop­erty Bureau’s as­sets – es­ti­mated to be worth at least US$40 billion (S$54.3 billion) – mak­ing him one of the rich­est roy­als in the world.</p>
    <p>MAY 2019</p>
    <p>He is of­fi­cially crowned on May 4. Days be­fore the corona­tion, he mar­ries long-time part­ner Suthida Va­ji­ra­longkorn, mak­ing her queen in his fourth mar­riage.</p>
    <p>JULY</p>
    <p>He be­stows the ti­tle of Royal No­ble Con­sort on for­mer army nurse Si­neenat Wong­va­ji­ra­pakdi.</p>
    <p>OC­TO­BER</p>
    <p>He dis­misses Ms Si­neenat for be­ing dis­loyal and un­grate­ful. In the days that fol­low, he sacks nearly a dozen palace of­fi­cials.</p>
    <p>March 2020</p>
    <p>The coro­n­avirus pandemic trig­gers a rare surge of on­line posts in Thai­land ques­tion­ing the monar­chy, with the Thai-lan­guage hash­tag roughly trans­lat­ing to #why­dowe­needak­ing?</p>
    <p>JUNE</p>
    <p>Protests break out over the al­leged kid­nap­ping of a pro-democ­racy ac­tivist. Prime Min­is­ter Prayut Chan-o-cha says the King has in­structed that the lese ma­jeste law be sus­pended. Mr Prayut still warns against crit­i­cism of the monar­chy.</p>
    <p>JULY – AU­GUST</p>
    <p>Protesters call for the gov­ern­ment to re­sign, along with veiled ref­er­ences chal­leng­ing the monar­chy. The ral­lies gain mo­men­tum and de­mands to re­form the monar­chy get more di­rect.</p>
    <p>SEPTEM­BER</p>
    <p>For­mer royal con­sort, Ms Si­neenat, is re­in­stated.</p>
    <p>OC­TO­BER</p>
    <p>As ten­sions es­ca­late, the King ap­pears in a broad­cast on state tele­vi­sion say­ing that “the coun­try needs peo­ple who love the coun­try and love the monar­chy”.</p>


